1
00:00:00,719 --> 00:00:04,649
为什么有些司机对切萨皮克湾大桥感到恐惧？
Why do some drivers dread the Chesapeake Bay Bridge?

2
00:00:04,649 --> 00:00:08,060
嗯，对一些人来说，这种恐惧在上桥之前就开始了。
Well, for some, it starts before they ever are on it.

3
00:00:08,059 --> 00:00:11,577
道路开始爬升，水面在两侧展开。
The road begins to climb and the water opens up on both sides.

4
00:00:11,578 --> 00:00:16,220
从岸边看起来可控的景象，突然间感觉完全不同了。
And what looked manageable from the shore suddenly feels very different.

5
00:00:16,220 --> 00:00:20,400
按现代标准来看，这座桥很高、暴露且狭窄。
This bridge is high, exposed, and narrow by modern standards.

6
00:00:20,400 --> 00:00:22,140
一旦你上了桥，
And once you commit to it,

7
00:00:22,140 --> 00:00:23,411
接下来的4.3英里就没有路肩，
there's no shoulder

8
00:00:23,411 --> 00:00:26,690
也没有方便的地方可以停下来。
and no easy place to stop for the next 4.3 miles.

9
00:00:26,690 --> 00:00:31,187
在航运通道处，桥面高出水面186英尺，
At the shipping channel, the deck rises 186 feet above the water,

10
00:00:31,187 --> 00:00:34,923
大约相当于18层公寓楼的高度，
about the same height as an 18story apartment building

11
00:00:34,924 --> 00:00:38,937
而桥塔比自由女神像还要高得多。
with bridge towers much higher than the Statue of Liberty.

12
00:00:38,936 --> 00:00:41,994
更不用说，这座桥还声名在外，
Add to that that this crossing has a reputation.

13
00:00:41,994 --> 00:00:42,886
很少有其他桥梁能与之相比。
Few others do.

14
00:00:42,887 --> 00:00:45,366
事实上，有些司机不只是不喜欢它，
In fact, some drivers don't just dislike it,

15
00:00:45,366 --> 00:00:47,282
他们甚至会雇人来
they'll actually hire someone else

16
00:00:47,281 --> 00:00:49,704
替他们开车过桥。
to take the wheel and drive them across it.

17
00:00:49,704 --> 00:00:52,930
但这种不安的感觉并非与这座桥的故事无关。
But that uneasy feeling is not separate from the story.

18
00:00:52,929 --> 00:00:56,251
切萨皮克湾大桥之所以是现在这个样子、给人这样的感觉，
The Chesapeake Bay Bridge looks and feel the way it is

19
00:00:56,251 --> 00:00:59,573
是因为它是为了解决一个非常具体的问题而建造的。
because it was built to solve a very specific problem.

20
00:00:59,572 --> 00:01:03,454
马里兰州需要一座足够高的通道来跨越主要航运通道，
Maryland needed a crossing high enough to clear a major shipping channel,

21
00:01:03,454 --> 00:01:05,740
足够坚固以抵御恶劣天气，
strong enough to withstand violent weather,

22
00:01:05,740 --> 00:01:09,675
并且足够高效，能够以渡轮永远无法做到的方式
and efficient enough to connect the Eastern Shore to the rest of the state

23
00:01:09,675 --> 00:01:11,217
将东岸与本州其他地区连接起来。
in a way fairies never could.

24
00:01:11,217 --> 00:01:14,136
恰恰是那些让这座桥令人望而生畏的因素，
The very things that make this bridge intimidating

25
00:01:14,136 --> 00:01:17,580
与使之成为可能的工程技术直接相关。
are directly tied to the engineering that made it possible.

26
00:01:17,580 --> 00:01:22,548
在其74年的服役生涯中，这是一个随着每一代人而改变的故事。
Over its 74 years service, it's a story that has changed with every generation.

27
00:01:22,548 --> 00:01:26,050
而现在，在2026年，这个故事再次发生了变化。
And now in 2026, that story has changed again.

28
00:01:26,050 --> 00:01:30,616
因为这不再仅仅是一个著名的地标或世纪中期的胜利。
Because this is no longer just a famous landmark or a mid-century triumph.

29
00:01:30,615 --> 00:01:33,534
这是一座承载着现代交通流量的老化通道，
It's an aging crossing carrying modern traffic,

30
00:01:33,534 --> 00:01:35,211
面临着现代海上风险，
facing modern maritime risk

31
00:01:35,211 --> 00:01:37,074
迫使马里兰州做出决定：
and forcing Maryland to decide

32
00:01:37,074 --> 00:01:40,987
当一个旧时代的方案在截然不同的时代仍在承担着关键使命时，
what happens when an old answer is still doing an essential job

33
00:01:40,986 --> 00:01:42,477
该怎么办。
in a very different era.

34
00:01:42,478 --> 00:01:43,492
我叫斯科特，
My name is Scott

35
00:01:43,492 --> 00:01:47,105
今天我们将以"不可能的工程"的视角，
and today we're taking an Engineering the Impossible look

36
00:01:47,106 --> 00:01:49,768
来看一座过桥令人生畏、
at a bridge that is intimidating to cross,

37
00:01:49,768 --> 00:01:51,226
运营复杂
complicated to operate,

38
00:01:51,226 --> 00:01:53,508
且有着迷人历史的大桥。
and shaped by a fascinating history.

39
00:01:53,589 --> 00:01:55,973
这就是切萨皮克湾大桥。
This is the Chesapeake Bay Bridge.

40
00:01:55,974 --> 00:01:58,160
让我们《越过出口》。
Let's go beyond the exit.

41
00:02:07,439 --> 00:02:10,370
切萨皮克湾大桥之所以如此让人紧张，
What makes the Chesapeake Bay Bridge so stressful

42
00:02:10,370 --> 00:02:13,840
是因为它不再像是通向它的那条高速公路。
is that it stops behaving like the highway that led to it.

43
00:02:13,840 --> 00:02:19,238
US50和US301在接近大桥时是六车道，每个方向三条。
US50 and US301 approach the crossing as six lanes, three in each direction.

44
00:02:19,238 --> 00:02:23,418
然后大桥将其压缩为横跨海湾总共五车道，
Then the bridge compresses that down to five lanes total across the bay,

45
00:02:23,418 --> 00:02:26,495
东向桥跨两条，西向桥跨三条。
two on the eastbound span and three on the westbound.

46
00:02:26,495 --> 00:02:30,160
要知道，这可不是一座车流量小的超大型桥梁。
Now, this is not some oversized bridge carrying light traffic.

47
00:02:30,160 --> 00:02:34,939
1952年通车时，它的年通行量仅略超过一百万辆。
When it opened in 1952, it carried just over a million vehicles.

48
00:02:34,939 --> 00:02:37,330
如今，它成了这条走廊的瓶颈，
Today, it's a choke point in the corridor,

49
00:02:37,330 --> 00:02:41,030
承载着现代交通需求，却用的是另一个时代的几何结构。
carrying the modern demand on geometry that was from another era.

50
00:02:41,029 --> 00:02:44,920
近期每年有超过2700万辆车次从这里通过。
More than 27 million crossings a year have been pushed through here lately.

51
00:02:44,920 --> 00:02:46,822
一旦你驶到水面上，
And once you're out over the water,

52
00:02:46,822 --> 00:02:49,920
大桥几乎没有给你留下多少额外的操作空间。
the bridge gives you very little extra room to work with.

53
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:53,194
这也是为什么过桥的感觉与身后道路如此不同的部分原因。
Part of why the crossing feels so different from the road behind it.

54
00:02:53,194 --> 00:02:57,380
它不仅又长又高，而且在风险升高的同时，空间却在收紧。
It's not just long and tall, it tightens down while the stakes go up.

55
00:02:57,380 --> 00:03:01,490
马里兰州多年来一直在努力从这种几何结构中挤出更多通行能力。
Maryland has spent years trying to ring more capacity out of that geometry.

56
00:03:01,490 --> 00:03:03,277
在东向交通繁忙时，
Under heavy eastbound traffic,

57
00:03:03,277 --> 00:03:06,017
西向桥跨的一条车道可以反向，
one lane of the westbound span can be reversed

58
00:03:06,017 --> 00:03:09,352
形成通往东岸的第三条车道。
to create a third lane heading toward the eastern shore.

59
00:03:09,352 --> 00:03:13,010
在条件允许的情况下，这种设置每年使用超过200天，
Whether permitting, that setup is used more than 200 days a year,

60
00:03:13,010 --> 00:03:15,261
而且这肯定是有代价的。
and it definitely comes with trade-offs.

61
00:03:15,261 --> 00:03:19,599
当这种情况发生时，该桥跨上对向行驶的车辆之间没有分隔带。
There is no divider between the opposing traffic on that span when it happens.

62
00:03:19,599 --> 00:03:23,760
所以，车速通常会降低，重型车辆还会面临车道限制。
So, speeds generally drop and heavier vehicles face lane restrictions.

63
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:29,497
马里兰州如今依靠架空车道控制信号、自动摆动闸门和双向通行设置，
Maryland now relies on overhead lane controls, automated swing gates, and two-way traffic setups

64
00:03:29,497 --> 00:03:31,947
来让这座已无法匹配其接入道路的通道发挥更多余力。
to squeeze more life out of this crossing

65
00:03:31,947 --> 00:03:34,815
来让这座已无法匹配其接入道路的通道发挥更多余力。
that no longer matches the road feeding into it.

66
00:03:34,815 --> 00:03:37,795
所以，这座桥现在不仅仅是在承载交通。
So, the bridge now is not just carrying traffic.

67
00:03:37,795 --> 00:03:40,728
它几乎得像一台机器一样被管理。
It has to be managed almost like it's a machine.

68
00:03:40,728 --> 00:03:42,935
而且即使这种灵活性也有其极限。
And even that flexibility has limits.

69
00:03:42,935 --> 00:03:45,920
在发布大风警报期间，双向通行是被禁止的。
Two-way traffic is prohibited during wind warnings.

70
00:03:45,920 --> 00:03:47,726
风速从30英里/小时到55英里/小时不等，
Anywhere from 30 mph up to 55,

71
00:03:47,726 --> 00:03:51,036
达到55英里/小时时，大桥将完全关闭。
which is where they'll completely shut the bridge down.

72
00:03:51,036 --> 00:03:55,360
这就是为什么司机们常说这座桥会让他们心神不宁。
And that's why drivers often say that this bridge gets in their heads.

73
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:58,601
你永远不知道驶上桥时会面对什么情况。
You never know exactly what you're going to face when you drive onto it.

74
00:03:58,601 --> 00:04:01,967
好，这部分故事告诉我们目前的处境。
Now, this part of the story tells us where we are right now.

75
00:04:01,967 --> 00:04:06,281
下一个问题是，马里兰州一开始是如何走到这一步的？
The next question is, how did Maryland get here in the first place?

76
00:04:06,281 --> 00:04:11,003
在湾桥建成之前，切萨皮克湾不仅仅是地图上的一片水域。
Before the Bay Bridge existed, the Chesapeake was not just water on a map.

77
00:04:11,003 --> 00:04:12,956
它是一道真正的交通障碍。
It was a real transportation barrier.

78
00:04:12,955 --> 00:04:15,122
汽车和卡车必须依靠渡轮，
Cars and trucks had to use fairies,

79
00:04:15,122 --> 00:04:17,846
而绕行海湾北端
and going around the northern end of the bay

80
00:04:17,846 --> 00:04:21,127
可能意味着大约200英里的旅程，
could mean a trip of roughly 200 miles on older roads

81
00:04:21,127 --> 00:04:23,727
走的是狭窄、别扭且缓慢的旧公路。
that were often narrow, awkward, and slow.

82
00:04:23,727 --> 00:04:25,437
到了20世纪中叶，
By the middle of the 20th century,

83
00:04:25,437 --> 00:04:27,600
整个系统已经难以为继。
that whole system was no longer keeping up.

84
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,573
对于东岸的居民来说，
For people on the Eastern Shore,

85
00:04:29,573 --> 00:04:31,607
这道障碍以如今听起来很奇怪的方式
that barrier shaped everyday life

86
00:04:31,607 --> 00:04:33,518
塑造着日常生活。
in ways that sound strange now.

87
00:04:33,518 --> 00:04:35,678
正如东岸的一则记载所言，
As one Eastern Shore account put it,

88
00:04:35,678 --> 00:04:37,898
对一些农民和海产品商贩来说，
for some farmers and seafood sellers,

89
00:04:37,898 --> 00:04:41,558
去费城的市场往往
it could often be easier to reach the markets in Philadelphia

90
00:04:41,559 --> 00:04:44,019
比费力地走漫长的公路去巴尔的摩更容易，
than to fight the long road to Baltimore,

91
00:04:44,019 --> 00:04:46,241
这正说明了在建桥之前，
which just shows how before the bridge,

92
00:04:46,241 --> 00:04:48,804
海湾不仅仅分隔了两条海岸线。
the bay did not just separate two shorelines.

93
00:04:48,804 --> 00:04:50,762
它扭曲了整个州的地理版图。
It warped the whole map of the state.

94
00:04:50,762 --> 00:04:53,439
建桥的压力已酝酿多年。
Pressure for a bridge had been building for years.

95
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:56,080
立法最终于1938年推动。
Legislation finally moved in 1938.

96
00:04:56,800 --> 00:04:59,520
随后第二次世界大战将项目推迟。
Then World War II pushed the project back.

97
00:04:59,520 --> 00:05:00,787
直到1947年，
It wasn't until 1947,

98
00:05:00,787 --> 00:05:03,985
特别是在州长小威廉·普雷斯顿·莱恩的领导下，
specifically under Governor William Preston Lane Jr.,

99
00:05:03,985 --> 00:05:07,666
州政府才终于承诺
that the state finally committed to building a fixed crossing

100
00:05:07,666 --> 00:05:09,838
在桑迪角和肯特岛之间修建一座固定通道。
between Sandy Point and Kent Island.

101
00:05:10,639 --> 00:05:14,314
然而，即便如此，许多人仍然认为这整个想法是鲁莽的。
Even then, though, many people thought that the whole idea was reckless.

102
00:05:14,314 --> 00:05:17,734
在成为地标之前，湾桥是一场巨大的赌博，
Before it became a landmark, the Bay Bridge was a big gamble,

103
00:05:17,734 --> 00:05:23,116
一次雄心勃勃的尝试，试图在马里兰州最大的障碍之一上强修一条永久性道路。
a hugely ambitious attempt to force a permanent road across one of Maryland's biggest obstacles.

104
00:05:23,116 --> 00:05:25,015
渡轮不可能永远维持下去。
Fairies could not keep pace forever.

105
00:05:25,015 --> 00:05:27,462
虽然它们的运输数量听起来惊人，
And while their numbers sound staggering,

106
00:05:27,462 --> 00:05:31,939
但每年仅能运送约10万辆车次穿越海湾。
they were only able to move about 100,000 vehicles annually across the bay.

107
00:05:31,938 --> 00:05:36,993
作为对比，大桥通车的1952年，
For a backdrop to that number, the first year the bridge was opened in 1952,

108
00:05:36,993 --> 00:05:39,520
第一年就承载了近110万辆车次。
it hosted nearly 1.1 million vehicles.

109
00:05:41,280 --> 00:05:43,920
所以，决定建桥是一回事，
So deciding to build a bridge was one thing.

110
00:05:43,920 --> 00:05:48,240
弄清楚哪种桥梁能真正在这里行得通则是另一回事。
Figuring out what kind of bridge could actually work here quite another.

111
00:05:48,240 --> 00:06:00,112
人们对湾桥——至少是1952年建成的原始桥跨——最先注意到的特征之一，是它几乎看起来像有人试图建造一个美国所有桥梁类型的样品套装。
One of the first things people notice about the Bay Bridge, at least the original span that was built in 52, is that it almost looks like somebody tried to build a sample kit of every bridge type in America.

112
00:06:00,112 --> 00:06:02,380
但这种混合外观是有其用途的。
But that mixed look has a purpose.

113
00:06:02,380 --> 00:06:05,225
没有任何一种单一设计能完成全部任务。
No single design could do the whole job.

114
00:06:05,225 --> 00:06:06,378
在西岸附近，
Near the Western Shore,

115
00:06:06,378 --> 00:06:09,638
桥梁必须升得足够高以跨越主航运通道。
the bridge had to rise enough to clear the main shipping channel.

116
00:06:09,638 --> 00:06:12,966
湾桥的其他部分不需要这种结构，
Other parts of the Bay Bridge didn't need that kind of structure,

117
00:06:12,966 --> 00:06:15,219
所以通道随着海湾本身而变化。
so the crossing changed with the bay itself.

118
00:06:15,219 --> 00:06:18,127
悬索桥承载着主通道上方的道路。
Suspension spans carried the road over the main channel.

119
00:06:18,128 --> 00:06:22,226
悬臂和桁架部分处理其他通航开口。
Canol lever and truss sections handled the other navigational openings.

120
00:06:22,226 --> 00:06:24,443
在较浅水域和航运需求不同的地方，
Lower beam and girder approaches took over

121
00:06:24,443 --> 00:06:28,720
较低的梁桥和连续梁引桥接替了任务。
where the water was shallower and the demands of shipping traffic were different.

122
00:06:28,720 --> 00:06:30,841
这种混合设计值得注意，
That mixed design is worth noticing

123
00:06:30,841 --> 00:06:33,205
因为它有助于解释
because it helps explain why the bridge

124
00:06:33,205 --> 00:06:35,690
为什么这座桥即便到现在开起来仍然感觉如此不同寻常。
still feels so unusual to drive even now.

125
00:06:35,690 --> 00:06:39,909
连大桥的那个大弯道也源自功能，而非美学。
Even the bridge's big curve comes from function, not aesthetics.

126
00:06:39,909 --> 00:06:43,434
主跨必须以直角跨越航运通道，
The main span had to cross the shipping channel at a right angle

127
00:06:43,434 --> 00:06:45,912
而这个要求塑造了驾驶体验本身。
and that requirement shaped the drive itself.

128
00:06:45,913 --> 00:06:49,765
但在图纸上解决通道问题只是挑战的一部分。
But solving the crossing on paper was only part of the challenge.

129
00:06:49,764 --> 00:06:53,119
在实地建造它则是完全另一个问题。
Building it out there was another problem entirely.

130
00:06:54,319 --> 00:06:58,221
原始通道由巴尔的摩的J. Grinder公司设计，
The original crossing was designed by Baltimore's J Grinder Company

131
00:06:58,221 --> 00:07:01,599
主要钢构件由Bethlehem Steel制造。
with major steel components fabricated by Bethlehem Steel.

132
00:07:01,599 --> 00:07:06,024
超过2000名工人投入了超过600万工时，
More than 2,000 workers spent over six million man-hour on the project

133
00:07:06,024 --> 00:07:08,552
钢构件通过驳船运来，
with steel sections carried out by barge

134
00:07:08,552 --> 00:07:11,776
由浮式起重机和固定式起重机吊装到位。
and lifted into place by floating and fixed cranes.

135
00:07:11,776 --> 00:07:16,460
施工期间，一些工人甚至住在浮动旅馆里。
Some workers were even housed in a floating hotel during construction.

136
00:07:16,460 --> 00:07:20,050
它必须逐步向开阔水域推进建造。
It had to be built progressively farther out over open water.

137
00:07:20,050 --> 00:07:23,290
这是一项大型且艰巨的海上工程，
Under the conditions of a large and demanding marine job,

138
00:07:23,290 --> 00:07:26,018
在上部结构安装是一项重大任务的同时，
while fitting the superructure was a major task,

139
00:07:26,018 --> 00:07:28,746
更艰难的战斗发生在水线以下。
the harder fight was found below the water line.

140
00:07:28,746 --> 00:07:31,773
施工人员面对的不是方便的浅层基岩。
Crews were not working with convenient shallow bedrock.

141
00:07:31,773 --> 00:07:35,710
切萨皮克湾只有深厚的沉积物、淤泥和埋藏的地层，
The Chesapeake only offered deep sediments, mud, and buried layers

142
00:07:35,710 --> 00:07:38,335
这使得湾底远不如
that made the bay floor far less cooperative

143
00:07:38,335 --> 00:07:41,199
建成后的大桥所显示的那么合作。
than the finished bridge actually makes it look.

144
00:07:41,199 --> 00:07:44,505
第一项工作是创建稳定的桥墩基础。
The first job was to create a stable pier foundation.

145
00:07:44,505 --> 00:07:48,040
首先建造巨大的钢制模板——称为沉箱，
Enormous steel forums called quesons were built first,

146
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:50,332
然后将其沉入湾底。
then sunk to the bottom of the bay.

147
00:07:50,333 --> 00:07:54,532
为了将它们固定到位，以不同角度穿过沉箱打入桩柱，
To hold them in place, piles were driven down through them at different angles,

148
00:07:54,532 --> 00:07:57,562
希望能通过摩擦力在底部获得抓力。
hoping to gain a purchase through friction at the bottom.

149
00:07:57,561 --> 00:08:02,482
之后，将一种特殊的水下固化混凝土注入每个沉箱，
After that, a special mix of underwater curing concrete was injected into each one

150
00:08:02,482 --> 00:08:04,223
以置换内部的水。
to displace the water inside.

151
00:08:04,223 --> 00:08:07,446
这些基础被允许固化，然后封顶，
These foundations were allowed to cure and then capped

152
00:08:07,446 --> 00:08:11,445
桥墩就建在它们上面，以承载上部结构。
and the peers were built on top of those to carry the superructure.

153
00:08:11,445 --> 00:08:14,492
工人们在这里需要达到的精度
The precision that workers had to achieve here

154
00:08:14,492 --> 00:08:18,003
通常在大多数情况下在半英寸以内，
was usually within a half an inch in most situations,

155
00:08:18,003 --> 00:08:22,044
考虑到那是在20世纪50年代初，这似乎几乎荒谬。
which seems almost absurd considering it was the early 1950s.

156
00:08:22,044 --> 00:08:24,475
他们没有GPS，没有计算机模型。
They had no GPS, no computer models.

157
00:08:24,475 --> 00:08:27,537
然而，从大桥今天的地位来看，
And yet, it's obvious with the bridgeg's status today,

158
00:08:27,537 --> 00:08:29,919
显然建造它的人并不缺乏技术。
there was no lack of skill in building it.

159
00:08:29,919 --> 00:08:33,496
那座1952年的原始桥跨确实是一项了不起的成就。
That original 1952 span was quite an achievement.

160
00:08:33,496 --> 00:08:36,270
它不是一座简单的桥梁重复数英里。
It wasn't one simple bridge repeated for miles.

161
00:08:36,270 --> 00:08:38,028
它是一堆问题，
It was a stack of problems

162
00:08:38,028 --> 00:08:42,560
以及由艰难的通道条件所迫的一堆更大的解决方案。
and an even larger stack of answers forced by a difficult crossing.

163
00:08:42,560 --> 00:08:46,880
但一旦那个问题被解决，它实际上又创造了另一个问题。
But once that problem was solved, it actually created another one.

164
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,903
当第一座桥跨于1952年7月30日开通时，
When the first span opened on July 30th, 1952,

165
00:08:50,903 --> 00:08:53,932
它并没有被当作普通的基础设施来对待。
it was not treated like ordinary infrastructure.

166
00:08:53,932 --> 00:08:58,399
当时，它是世界上最长的水上钢桥。
At the time, it was the world's longest overwater steel bridge.

167
00:08:58,399 --> 00:09:01,196
对马里兰州来说，这是与过去真正的决裂。
For Maryland, it was a genuine break with the past.

168
00:09:01,196 --> 00:09:05,167
曾经受天气、等待和不确定性影响的渡轮通道，
What had been a ferry crossing shaped by weather, waiting, and uncertainty

169
00:09:05,167 --> 00:09:07,474
现在变成了一条直接横跨海湾的公路。
was now a direct road right across the bay.

170
00:09:07,473 --> 00:09:11,536
所有那些都已被绕开，这听起来像是一场巨大的胜利。
All of that had been bypassed, and that sounds like a huge triumph.

171
00:09:11,536 --> 00:09:13,427
而在当时，这确实是。
And for the time, it definitely was.

172
00:09:13,427 --> 00:09:16,290
但这也意味着，
But it also meant that the bridge started aging

173
00:09:16,290 --> 00:09:18,788
这座桥几乎立刻就进入了下一个问题的老化期。
into its next problem almost immediately.

174
00:09:18,788 --> 00:09:22,560
它不仅仅是在满足需求，它也在创造需求。
It wasn't just serving demand. It was also creating it.

175
00:09:22,560 --> 00:09:26,480
而这，确实是切萨皮克湾大桥的核心矛盾。
And really, that's a contradiction at the heart of the Chesapeake Bay Bridge.

176
00:09:26,480 --> 00:09:29,562
它以奇迹之姿开放，但没过多久就不再显得容量过剩了。
It opened as a marvel, but it didn't stay oversized for long.

177
00:09:29,562 --> 00:09:32,720
可以说，它成了自身成功的受害者。
You could say it became a victim of its own success.

178
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:35,436
这座通道使东岸更加可达，
The crossing made the Eastern Shore more reachable

179
00:09:35,436 --> 00:09:38,043
当然也减少了对渡轮的依赖，
and it cut dependence on the fairies, of course,

180
00:09:38,043 --> 00:09:41,900
但同时也将旅游、通勤和商业拉入了一个新时代。
and yet it helped pull tourism, commuting, and commerce into a new era.

181
00:09:41,900 --> 00:09:44,000
这种成功是有代价的。
That success came with a cost.

182
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:48,576
原始桥梁只有两条车道，每个方向一条，
The original bridge carried only two lanes, one in each direction,

183
00:09:48,576 --> 00:09:50,933
而交通增长如此之快，
and traffic growth came so quickly

184
00:09:50,934 --> 00:09:55,995
以至于马里兰州在一代人之内就开始规划更多容量。
that Maryland was already planning for more capacity within a generation.

185
00:09:55,995 --> 00:09:59,002
1969年，在第一条桥跨以北约450英尺处，
In 1969, construction began on a second span

186
00:09:59,002 --> 00:10:01,462
第二座桥跨开工建设。
about 450 ft north of the first one.

187
00:10:01,543 --> 00:10:06,901
1973年6月28日，那座新的三车道桥梁通车。
And on June 28th, 1973, that new threelane bridge opened to traffic.

188
00:10:06,901 --> 00:10:09,963
1973年的西向桥跨不仅仅是
Now, the 73 westbound span was not simply a copy

189
00:10:09,963 --> 00:10:11,239
第一座桥的复制品。
of the first bridge.

190
00:10:11,240 --> 00:10:22,941
它反映了二十年的工程变革，以及不同的施工方式，上部结构由US Steel的美国桥梁部门建造，下部结构由Raymond Dravo Langenfelter负责。
It reflected two decades of engineering change and a different construction effort with the American Bridge Division of US Steel building the superructure and Raymond Dravo Langenfelter handling the substructure.

191
00:10:22,940 --> 00:10:28,504
不变的是，Grryer仍然是该项目的设计和监理工程师。
What remained the same was Grryer remained the design and supervising engineer of the project.

192
00:10:28,504 --> 00:10:32,329
较新的桥跨在细节上也明显更加现代化。
The newer span was also visibly more modern in its details.

193
00:10:32,329 --> 00:10:37,988
它采用了水平塔架支撑，而不是原始桥跨上使用的X形支撑。
It used horizontal tower bracing rather than X bracing that was used on the original span.

194
00:10:37,988 --> 00:10:41,305
而且斜拉索不是位于水面高度，
And the cable stays rather than being at the water level

195
00:10:41,305 --> 00:10:43,082
而是位于桥面高度。
were at the bridge deck level.

196
00:10:43,082 --> 00:10:44,591
这不仅仅是更多的桥。
It was not just more bridge.

197
00:10:44,592 --> 00:10:48,556
这是马里兰州让这座跨海通道适应交通需求的下一次尝试。
It was Maryland's next attempt to adapt the crossing to traffic demands.

198
00:10:48,556 --> 00:10:50,652
第一座桥跨很快就无法满足需求了。
The first span had quickly outgrown.

199
00:10:50,651 --> 00:10:54,867
所以人们今天穿越的这座桥实际上是两个不同时代的产物。
So the bridge people cross today is really the product of two different eras.

200
00:10:54,867 --> 00:10:57,650
第一座桥跨是为了终结渡轮瓶颈而建造的，
A first span that was built to end the ferry bottleneck

201
00:10:57,650 --> 00:11:00,585
并证明了海湾确实可以通过公路穿越。
and proved that the bay could be crossed by a road at all.

202
00:11:00,585 --> 00:11:03,769
第二座桥跨则是在后来建成的，
The second span came later after traffic had grown enough

203
00:11:03,769 --> 00:11:07,624
当时交通量已经增长到足以证明最初的方案本身已不够用了。
to show that the original answer was no longer big enough on its own.

204
00:11:07,625 --> 00:11:09,690
而它所创造的就是
And what it created is the bridge

205
00:11:09,690 --> 00:11:12,569
马里兰州自那以后一直在使用的这座桥。
that Maryland has been living with ever since.

206
00:11:12,569 --> 00:11:16,800
一个已有50多年历史的解决方案，至今仍在艰难地勉力维持。
The solution that's over 50 years old, still struggling to keep up.

207
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:21,973
到了那时，困难的部分已不再是在海湾上架起一座桥。
By then, the hard part was no longer getting a bridge across the bay.

208
00:11:21,973 --> 00:11:25,031
困难的部分是马里兰州已经离不开这座桥了。
The hard part was that Maryland had become dependent on one.

209
00:11:25,031 --> 00:11:28,566
切萨皮克湾大桥太重要不能失去，太繁忙不能关闭，
The Bay Bridge was too important to lose, too busy to shut down,

210
00:11:28,566 --> 00:11:31,328
也太难以在短时间内被替换。
and too difficult to replace on a quick timetable.

211
00:11:31,328 --> 00:11:35,206
从那时起，这座桥的故事就变成了管理、维修和风险的故事。
From that point on, the story becomes one of management, repair, and risk.

212
00:11:35,206 --> 00:11:38,333
也是从那时起，这座桥开始给人一种不同的感觉。
And it's also where the bridge began to feel different.

213
00:11:38,333 --> 00:11:43,344
不再是一座马里兰州建成的奇迹，而是一个该州不得不不断修补、保护和谨慎运营的通道，
Not a marvel Maryland had built, but a crossing that the state had to keep patching, protecting,

214
00:11:43,344 --> 00:11:46,267
因为有太多东西依赖它。
and carefully operating because too much depended on it.

215
00:11:46,267 --> 00:11:49,047
桥梁安全也是其中的一个重要因素。
Bridge safety was a major factor of that as well.

216
00:11:49,046 --> 00:11:53,016
2008年，一辆牵引拖车撞穿了部分护栏，
In 2008, a tractor trailer crash tore through part of the barrier

217
00:11:53,016 --> 00:11:54,970
导致卡车坠入海湾。
and sent the truck into the bay.

218
00:11:54,970 --> 00:11:59,284
随后的调查指向了比单一起事故更令人担忧的问题。
The investigation that followed pointed to something more troubling than a single wreck.

219
00:11:59,284 --> 00:12:03,040
护栏系统本身的某些部分已被腐蚀削弱。
Parts of the barrier system itself had been weakened by corrosion.

220
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:06,624
这就是那种揭示切萨皮克湾大桥已经成为什么的时刻。
That was the kind of moment that showed what the Bay Bridge had become.

221
00:12:06,624 --> 00:12:10,375
一座日渐老化的基础设施，而该州却无法承受没有它的后果。
An aging piece of infrastructure that the state couldn't afford to do without.

222
00:12:10,375 --> 00:12:13,537
从那时起，这座桥的后期生涯
And from there, the bridge's later life starts to read

223
00:12:13,537 --> 00:12:15,352
就像一场漫长的保护之战。
like a long preservation fight.

224
00:12:15,352 --> 00:12:18,217
东行方向的桥面已经更换过一次。
The eastbound deck had already been replaced once.

225
00:12:18,217 --> 00:12:22,038
西行方向的桥跨也经历了一次大规模的修复。
The westbound span went through a major rehabilitation as well.

226
00:12:22,038 --> 00:12:25,207
到2010年代中期，马里兰州仍在
By the mid 2010s, Maryland was still finding

227
00:12:25,207 --> 00:12:28,160
以更隐蔽的方式发现这座桥的老化迹象。
the bridg's age in more hidden ways, too.

228
00:12:28,160 --> 00:12:34,707
两座桥跨的主悬索进行了重新包裹，
The main suspension cables on both spans were rewrapped and fitted with a special dehumidification system

229
00:12:34,707 --> 00:12:37,762
并安装了一套特殊的除湿系统，
to seal out moisture, dry the cables from inside,

230
00:12:37,762 --> 00:12:39,446
以隔绝湿气、从内部干燥缆索并减缓进一步的腐蚀。
and slow further corrosion.

231
00:12:39,606 --> 00:12:44,240
该项目于2012年秋季开始，2015年完成。
The project began in the fall of 2012 and was completed by 2015.

232
00:12:44,240 --> 00:12:48,280
该州还改变了桥梁本身的交通管理方式。
The state also changed how traffic was handled on the bridge itself.

233
00:12:48,280 --> 00:12:52,646
不再依赖更多的人工变道和较慢的设置，
Instead of relying on more manual lane changes and slower setup,

234
00:12:52,646 --> 00:12:59,059
这座跨海通道安装了自动化车道控制系统，
the crossing was fitted with an automated lane control system using overhead signals and gates

235
00:12:59,059 --> 00:13:02,675
使用高架信号灯和闸门，
so crews could close lanes, reverse traffic patterns,

236
00:13:02,675 --> 00:13:05,608
使工作人员能够关闭车道、逆转通行模式，并在情况变化时更快地做出响应。
and respond faster when conditions changed.

237
00:13:05,608 --> 00:13:10,206
即使所有的自动化交通控制和安全意识措施都已到位，
Even with all of the automated traffic control and safety awareness in place,

238
00:13:10,206 --> 00:13:15,401
日益增长的交通量加上维持桥梁运行所必需的施工作业，
the increased traffic combined with the construction necessary to keep the bridge going

239
00:13:15,402 --> 00:13:20,000
几乎可以保证事故的发生，尤其是在如此狭窄的走廊中。
almost guarantees accidents will happen, especially in such a tight corridor.

240
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:24,701
根据该州在2017年至2022年间进行的一项研究，
According to a study between 2017 and 2022 performed by the state,

241
00:13:24,701 --> 00:13:29,473
切萨皮克湾大桥平均每年发生近100起事故，
the Chesapeake Bay Bridge averages nearly a 100 accidents per year,

242
00:13:29,472 --> 00:13:32,891
包括因大雾和天气导致的多车连环相撞，
including multi-car pileups from fog and weather

243
00:13:32,891 --> 00:13:37,378
以及奇怪的是，因分心驾驶导致的事故数量也在增长。
and strangely a number that have grown from distracted drivers.

244
00:13:37,378 --> 00:13:39,156
而每次事故发生，
And every time one occurs,

245
00:13:39,156 --> 00:13:43,054
都会将安全问题重新推到每个人的心头。
it jolts safety back to the forefront of everyone's mind.

246
00:13:43,054 --> 00:13:47,114
这种担忧即将迎来又一次重大冲击。
That concern was about to receive another major jolt.

247
00:13:47,114 --> 00:13:49,141
2024年，巴尔的摩的弗朗西斯·斯科特·基大桥坍塌
In 2024, the world was shocked

248
00:13:49,141 --> 00:13:52,925
震惊了世界。
by the collapse of Baltimore's Francis Scott Key Bridge.

249
00:13:52,925 --> 00:13:56,205
大多数人记得在视频中看到那些画面。
Most people remember seeing the images in the video play out.

250
00:13:56,205 --> 00:14:00,313
许多人不太记得清楚的是，为什么坍塌如此彻底。
What many don't remember as clearly is why the collapse was so complete.

251
00:14:00,313 --> 00:14:03,247
这座桥被集装箱船"多莉"号撞上，
The bridge was struck by the container ship Dolly

252
00:14:03,247 --> 00:14:08,098
当时该船在桥附近失去了电力、推进力和舵效。
after the vessel lost electrical power, propulsion, and steering near the bridge.

253
00:14:08,098 --> 00:14:11,932
当它撞上一根关键的支撑桥墩时，整个结构轰然倒塌。
When it hit a critical support pier, the structure gave way.

254
00:14:11,932 --> 00:14:15,589
这是一场看似不可能发生的灾难。
It was a disaster that seemed too impossible to happen.

255
00:14:15,589 --> 00:14:19,493
事故之后，这迫使马里兰州提出另一个棘手的问题。
In the aftermath, it forced Maryland to ask another hard question.

256
00:14:19,493 --> 00:14:22,019
切萨皮克湾大桥能经受住
Could the Bay Bridge survive being struck

257
00:14:22,019 --> 00:14:25,778
那种让基大桥倒塌的现代船只的撞击吗？
by the kind of modern ship that brought the key to its knees?

258
00:14:25,778 --> 00:14:28,123
答案是响亮的"不能"。
That answer was a resounding no.

259
00:14:28,123 --> 00:14:31,115
事实上，调查确定
In fact, from the investigation, it was determined

260
00:14:31,115 --> 00:14:35,604
切萨皮克湾大桥可能是全国最脆弱的桥梁之一。
that the Bay Bridge may be one of the most vulnerable in the entire nation.

261
00:14:35,604 --> 00:14:39,916
马里兰州对切萨皮克湾大桥的应对方案是
Maryland's answer at the Bay Bridge is a protection project

262
00:14:39,916 --> 00:14:42,620
一个估计耗资1.75亿美元的保护项目。
at an estimated cost of $175 million.

263
00:14:42,620 --> 00:14:44,666
该系统目前正在推进中，
That system is being advanced now,

264
00:14:44,666 --> 00:14:48,277
但仍处于设计、建造和采购阶段，
but it is still in the design, build, and procurement phase,

265
00:14:48,276 --> 00:14:50,707
而不是已经完工矗立在水面上，
not sitting finished out on the water,

266
00:14:50,707 --> 00:14:55,761
这就引出了马里兰州现在对这座桥提出的问题——
which brings Maryland to the question it is asking about this bridge right now.

267
00:14:55,761 --> 00:14:57,040
它的未来是什么？
What comes after it?

268
00:14:58,480 --> 00:15:03,228
马里兰州不再假装再多修补几次就能解决整个问题。
Maryland is no longer pretending a few more repairs will solve the whole problem.

269
00:15:03,228 --> 00:15:07,556
一项针对该桥的多年研究刚刚在去年完成。
A multi-year study of the bridge was concluded just this last year.

270
00:15:07,556 --> 00:15:12,294
而在2026年下半年，马里兰州交通管理局宣布
And in the latter part of 2026, Maryland Transit Authority announced

271
00:15:12,294 --> 00:15:15,917
将采用被称为"方案C"的计划，
that it would be adopting the plan labeled option C,

272
00:15:16,317 --> 00:15:21,740
即在现有跨海通道附近建造两座带有全路肩的新四车道桥跨，
two new four-lane bridge spans with full shoulders built near the existing crossing

273
00:15:21,740 --> 00:15:25,725
并最终拆除和移除现有桥跨。
and the eventual demolition and removal of the current spans.

274
00:15:25,726 --> 00:15:30,720
根据当前的研究时间表，最终的联邦决定预计在2026年做出。
Under the current study timeline, the final federal decision is expected in 2026.

275
00:15:30,720 --> 00:15:35,508
最终设计将于2028年开始，许可将在2031年跟进，
Final design would begin in 2028, permits would follow in 2031,

276
